s early life that shifts our focus and alters our priorities. Combining the latest scientific findings with real-life stories and experiences, Susan Brink examines critical dimensions of newborn development such as eating and nutrition, bonding and attachment, sleep patterns, sensory development, pain and pleasure, and the creation of foundations for future advancement. Brink offers well-informed, practical information and the reasons behind her advice so that parents and caretakers can make their own decisions about how to care for a newborn during this crucial period. The Fourth Trimester assures readers that infants are as biologically capable as they are physically helpless. They thrive on what is readily available in every household: consistent, loving attention.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aCommunity mental health services. 0aCommunity psychiatryxEthics. 0aCommunity psychiatry; Ethics. 0aInfantsxCare. 0aInfantsxDevelopment. 0aNewborn infantsxCare. 0aNewborn infantsxDevelopment. 7aMEDICAL / Health Care Delivery.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  aattachment.  abiological bridge.  abonding.  acaretakers.  achildbirth.  achildren.  aearly life.  aengaging.  afamily.  afetal life.  afourth trimester.  agender studies.  ahealth care delivery.  aintense development.  aloving attention.  anewborn babies.  anewborn development.  anewborn.  anutrition.  aoperating manual.  apage turner.  aparenting advice.  aparenting babies.  aparenting.  apractical information.  apregnancy.  aself help.  asensory development.  asleep patterns.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095451940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954519423Coveruhttps://www.degru